						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/To-feed-itself-Africa-must-capture-more-rainwater" title="To feed itself Africa must capture more rainwater" alt="link">To feed itself Africa must capture more rainwater</a></h2>

	
					<p><i>New Scientist, no. 2642, 28 August 2004, p.8</i>. Dams have had their day and underground water reserves are running dry. The only way to water and feed a growing population is to catch more rain. This is the preliminary conclusion of the Comprehensive Assessment of Water Management in Agriculture (CAWMA), a five-year international project aimed at solving the world's water crisis. The world's 2 billion poor farmers must be given access to low-cost technologies designed to capture rainwater. If Africa is to feed itself in 2050, it will have to increase rain-fed agriculture fivefold. That means Africa's leaders need to think beyond dams. See also the conclusions of the 2004 <a href="http://www.siwi.org/press/presrel_04_SWS%20Conclusions.htm" target="_blank">Stockholm Water Symposium</a> (August 2004).</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/To-feed-itself-Africa-must-capture-more-rainwater">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Mozambique-subsistence-agriculture-faces-long-term-decline-from-HIV-AIDS-epidemic" title="Mozambique subsistence agriculture faces long-term decline from HIV/AIDS epidemic" alt="link">Mozambique subsistence agriculture faces long-term decline from HIV/AIDS epidemic</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>FAO, 23 August 2004</i>. HIV/AIDS is threatening subsistence agriculture in Mozambique, and in countries across southern and eastern Africa, with long-term decline, a trend that has ominous implications for the country's food supply, FAO warned today. A new study of subsistence agriculture in Mozambique documents the loss of many varieties of grains, tubers, legumes and vegetables due to HIV/AIDS, flood and drought, according to FAO. The disease is impoverishing agricultural households. The study shows that 45% of respondents from HIV/AIDS-affected households said they had reduced the area under cultivation and 60% said they had reduced the number of crops grown. This study documents an alarming trend affecting millions of the poorest rural households.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Mozambique-subsistence-agriculture-faces-long-term-decline-from-HIV-AIDS-epidemic">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Forging-a-new-deal-for-scientific-cooperation" title="Forging a ‘new deal’ for scientific cooperation" alt="link">Forging a ‘new deal’ for scientific cooperation</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>DG Research, International Cooperation Newsletter, August 2004</i>. Over the past two decades, the international dimension of European research has come a long way. EU research programmes have opened up as never before to developing countries. Now, a new deal is needed for international scientific cooperation. Future research programmes must look further beyond the European dimension and focus on the global one. They should also reflect the growing geopolitical importance of knowledge. See also the <a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/research/iscp/pdf/inco-action-plan_en.pdf" target="_blank">INCO Action plan for FP6</a>.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Forging-a-new-deal-for-scientific-cooperation">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
