						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Overfishing-on-the-increase-in-Asia-Pacific-seas" title="Overfishing on the increase in Asia-Pacific seas" alt="link">Overfishing on the increase in Asia-Pacific seas</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>FAO, 6 August 2004.</i> The management of fishery resources in Asia-Pacific needs to be improved, as overfishing is increasing and the abundance of more valuable species has declined, according to an FAO report presented to the Asia-Pacific Fishery Commission (APFIC) this week. The report affirmed that fisheries and aquaculture are of vital importance for food security and the economies of the region, but cautioned that improved management of these activities is required in order to secure the sector's future. APFIC will take on a new role to act as a regional consultative forum to promote the sustainable development of fisheries and aquaculture in the region.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Overfishing-on-the-increase-in-Asia-Pacific-seas">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Banana-research-project-hits-snag" title="Banana research project hits snag" alt="link">Banana research project hits snag</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>New Vision (Kampala), 3 August 2004.</i> A plan by Kawanda Agricultural Research Institute (KARI) to produce genetically modified (GM) bananas has stalled due to lack of a biosafety law. Researchers at KARI were planning to produce disease-resistant and highly nutritious banana varieties using genetic engineering. Last year, President Museveni launched an ultramodern biotechnology lab in Kawanda where scientists would do genetic research until their products get approval before giving them to farmers. First, the Uganda National Council for Science and Technology (UNCST) should put in place the necessary legal framework. As a result of the delay in formulating biosafety laws, so would follow the late cultivation of GM crops.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Banana-research-project-hits-snag">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Uganda-Zambia-to-swap-scientists" title="Uganda, Zambia to swap scientists" alt="link">Uganda, Zambia to swap scientists</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>AllAfrica.com, 3 August 2004.</i> Uganda and Zambia are to start a scientist exchange programme to share innovations and technological developments for the improvement of exports, especially for the AGOA market. President Museveni has offered to send Ugandan scientists to Zambia to share their experiences and innovations, and to take advantage of science to add value to products for export and the eradication of poverty and hunger through improved agriculture.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Uganda-Zambia-to-swap-scientists">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-study-shows-aid-for-short-term-projects-has-positive-effects-on-economic-growth" title="New study shows aid for short-term projects has positive effects on economic growth" alt="link">New study shows aid for short-term projects has positive effects on economic growth</a></h2>

	
					<p> 
 <i>AllAfrica.com 30 July 2004</i>. The <a href="http://www.cgdev.org" target="_blank">Center for Global Development</a> has released a new study that examines the growth effects of short-impact aid - such as infrastructure building, agricultural or industry support, and financial assistance - in developing countries. The study found a positive, causal relationship between short-impact aid and economic growth over a four-year period. In addition, the analysis of growth rates in sub-Saharan Africa shows that increasing short-impact aid would increase growth by about one percentage point over standard aid flows.See <a href="http://www.cgdev.org/Publications/?PubID=130" target="_blank"> <i>Counting chickens when they hatch: short-term effect of aid on growth</i> </a>, M. Clemens <i>et al.,</i> CGD Working Paper 44, June 2004. </p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-study-shows-aid-for-short-term-projects-has-positive-effects-on-economic-growth">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-Netherlands-pledges-euro-20-million-euros-to-partnership-programme" title="The Netherlands pledges &amp;euro; 20 million euros to partnership programme" alt="link">The Netherlands pledges &amp;euro; 20 million euros to partnership programme</a></h2>

	
					<p> <i>FAO press release, 28 July 2004.</i> The Netherlands has pledged Euro 20 million to support the work of the FAO-Netherlands Partnership Programme (FNPP) over the next four years. The FNPP focuses on three key areas: food security, agricultural biodiversity and forestry. Within this framework, it supports FAO's work to build capacity in poor countries for development planning and policy-making. Activities undertaken by FAO with FNPP support range from the development of a coordinated forestry policy for central Africa, to studies in Ethiopia aimed at improving the efficiency of seed delivery systems.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-Netherlands-pledges-euro-20-million-euros-to-partnership-programme">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
